{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:50:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:50:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12756"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12756"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.06,0.06,0.18,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110291"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5203"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92562"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41417"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110291"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her GP with a 12 month history of intermittent episodes of abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. When it occurs, the pain is in her mid abdomen, occasionally radiating in a bandlike fashion to the middle of her back. She has also lost weight and has noticed that her stools are oily and foul-smelling. Her last episode of pain was about three weeks ago. Her medical history includes lupus nephritis for which she takes azathioprine and hydroxychloroquine. She has a 5-pack-year smoking history and drinks about four glasses of wine most evenings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 110/75mmHg, pulse 91/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The rest of her examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum lipase","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","Serum amylase","Ultrasound abdomen","CT abdomen"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation is suggestive of chronic pancreatitis. The oily and foul-smelling stools would be consistent with pancreatic insufficiency secondary to chronic pancreatitis. Current guidelines recommend either CT or MRI as the initial imaging modalities. Of those listed in the options, a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E scan is the most important initial investigation. It may show dilation of the main pancreatic duct, pancreatic calcification, changes in pancreatic size (i.e., atrophy), shape, and a contour suggestive of chronic pancreatitis or complications from chronic pancreatitis such as a pancreatic pseudocyst. It is the ideal test to image the abdomen and assess pancreas morphology and also helps in excluding other pathologies. In this case, her most likely cause of this is chronic alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lipase\u003C/strong\u003E and\u003Cstrong\u003E serum amylase\u003C/strong\u003E are enzymes that are produced by the pancreas and can be released into the blood when there is damage to the pancreas. Serum amylase and lipase levels may be slightly elevated in chronic pancreatitis; high levels are found only in acute pancreatitis. In the later stages of chronic pancreatitis, atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma can result in normal or even low serum enzyme levels because of significant fibrosis of the pancreas. However, low levels are not diagnostic for chronic pancreatitis and therefore CT is still the correct answer. Serum lipase and amylase are not diagnostic tests for chronic pancreatitis, and normal levels do not exclude chronic pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)\u003C/strong\u003E is an imaging test that uses magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) to visualise the bile ducts and pancreatic ducts. It can be used to evaluate patients with suspected pancreatic or biliary disorders. However, MRCP is a more invasive and expensive imaging study, hence it is not the most appropriate initial investigation in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound abdomen \u003C/strong\u003Eis a non-invasive diagnostic tool that can be used to evaluate the pancreas. However, the diagnosis of chronic pancreatitis can be difficult. The limitation of ultrasound is its inability to evaluate the complete pancreas due to patient body habitus and overlying bowel gas, making CT abdomen the most suitable imaging modality. An ultrasound could be considered if looking for gallstones as a cause of acute pancreatitis - but that is not the dynamic in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT abdomen is the most appropriate initial investigation for the diagnosis of chronic pancreatitis.","Serum lipase and amylase are not diagnostic tests for chronic pancreatitis, and normal levels do not exclude chronic pancreatitis."],"references":["Benjamin O, Lappin SL. Chronic Pancreatitis. [Updated 2022 Jun 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan. Available online: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482325/","Pham A, Forsmark C. Chronic pancreatitis: review and update of etiology, risk factors, and management. F1000Res. 2018;7. Available online: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29946424/","Dima A, Balaban D, Jurcut C, Jinga M. Systemic lupus erythematosis-related acute pancreatitis. Lupus. 2021;30(1):5-14. Available online: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33307986/","Oh HC, Kwon CI, El Hajj II, Easler JJ, Watkins J, Fogel EL, McHenry L, Sherman S, Zimmerman MK, Lehman GA. Low Serum Pancreatic Amylase and Lipase Values Are Simple and Useful Predictors to Diagnose Chronic Pancreatitis. Gut Liver. 2017 Nov 15;11(6):878-883. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5669605/","Hines OJ, Pandol SJ. Management of chronic pancreatitis. BMJ 2024; 384:e070920"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92562"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92562"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T15:08:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T15:09:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5203"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110291"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"